                    <msContents>
                        <summary>
                            
                            <p>On four detached stones lying in front of the Parāśarēśvara temple.</p>						
                            
                            <p>Vīrarājēndra. Year 7, Ś. 991: 1069-1070 A.D.</p>						
                            
                            <p>The inscription is dated in Śaka 991, Saumya and in the 7th year of the king's reign thus yielding the initial year 1063-64 A.D. It describes the king with the Chālukya titles like Sakalabhuvanāśraya, Mēdinīvallabha and Ravikula-tilaka, etc., and also commences with the <hi rend="italic">praśasti Vīramētuṇai-yāgavum</hi>, etc., of the king.</p>						
                            
                            <p>This seems to record some grant by the king, when he was seated in his palace on the banks of the river Pagaḷai, in Nuṟuṅgi in Vallakkunda-nāḍu in Vijayarājēndramaṇḍalam to god Pipplādīśvaramuḍaiya-mahādēva.</p>						
                            
                            <p>Four more pieces, apparently belonging to the same inscription seem to record the details of the grant.</p>
                            
                        </summary>
                    </msContents>
